@node Introduction "EPA Greek Workbench - Introduction"

  "EPA Greek Workbench" is a set of files that will allow you to select the
  Greek language as one of the languages that amiga will support. This has
  become possible thanks to locale.library that was introduced in the
  Workbench 2.1. From then on, one could select her language, and see most of
  the displayed messages and texts in it. One could also use the
  @{"included Latin-Greek fonts" link Fonts} as defaults in their favourite web browser,
  and thus be able to browse Greek web pages too.

  As an example the operating system came with support for the most common
  languages (other than English) such as German (Deutsch). But even if your
  language was not directly supported, you could build the necessary files and
  "localize" your Amiga yourself. That's what I did for me, and now I would
  like to share the product of months of work with whoever finds use in it.

  This is a Greek Workbench. That is, a localization of the Workbench so that
  the system messages (and not only) are in Greek. It would be safe to say,
  that in order to find use in it, one would have to be able to read and
  understand Greek. In other words, this will be mostly of use to Greeks.
@endnode

@node Requirements "EPA Greek Workbench - Requirements"

  The following are required to use "EPA Greek Workbench":

  ñ An Amiga running Workbench 2.1 or higher.
    (Localization was introduced with Workbench 2.1)

  ñ The Installer utility from Commodore-Amiga Inc., or even better, the one
    from ESCOM AG. (Version 43.3), is required for an automated @{"installation" link Installation} of
    the package, but you can also do it manually.
@endnode

@node Installation "EPA Greek Workbench - Installation"

In order to fully install EPA Greek Workbench, you have to do the following:

 @{" ñ " link CopyingFiles} Copy files to their places
 @{" ñ " link PatchTopaz} Patch the ROM Topaz 8 font
 @{" ñ " link KeymapChange} Automate the keymap change
@endnode

@node CopyingFiles "EPA Greek Workbench - Installation, Copying files to their places"

  @{b}Automated installation of files, using Installer(TM)@{ub}

    Double click on the icon labeled `Install' and follow instructions. For
    this to work, the program `Installer' should be somewhere in your system
    path.

  @{b}Manual installation of files@{ub}

    Copy everything in the `locale/' drawer, to LOCALE:
    You can do this from CLI by issuing "copy locale locale: all" from the
    directory EPAGrWb.

    Copy the @{"keymap files" link keymaps} found in `devs/keymaps/' to KEYMAPS:
    This assign should exist and usually points to DEVS:Keymaps. You can do
    this from CLI by issuing "copy devs/keymaps/#? keymaps:" from the directory
    EPAGrWb.

    Copy the @{"supplied Latin-Greek fonts" link Fonts} found in `fonts/' to FONTS:
    You can do this from CLI by issuing "copy fonts fonts: all" from the
    directory EPAGrWb.

    Copy `C/@{"ToggleKeymap" link ToggleKeymap}' and `C/@{"ReplaceTopaz" link ReplaceTopaz} to wherever you put CLI
    commands. This could be C:, SYS:Bin/ (if you have such a drawer),
    SYS:Utilities/, or whatever you think.
@endnode

@node Activation "EPA Greek Workbench - How to activate it"

  To activate the Greek Workbench you should:

  ñ Run the `Font' preferences program and select the
    @{"supplied Latin-Greek fonts" link Fonts} as defaults. I recommend helveticagr_SH as icon
    font, couriergr as system font, and helveticagr as screen font.
    (This action can also be performed by the installer if you choose so)

  ñ Run the `Locale' preferences program, click on `Clear Languages', then
    select `Greek' from `Available Languages', and `Greece' from `Country'.
    Then click on `Use', or `Save' for a permanent effect.
    (This action can also be performed by the installer if you choose so)

  ñ If you want to be able to browse Greek web pages, start your favourite web
    browser, find the font preferences, and set as default any of the
    @{"supplied Latin-Greek fonts" link Fonts}.

  After that, all system messages, dates, etc. should be in Greek. To get an
  idea of how @{"my" link Contact} Workbench looks like, download pix/wb/epawb.lha from Aminet.
@endnode

@node keymaps "EPA Greek Workbench - The keymaps"

  Two keymaps are supplied, USAELOT and ELOT928. (ELOT 928 is the most dominant
  standard for the ASCII codes of Greek characters in a 256 character set.)
  They were made by @{"me" link Contact} using @{"EditKeys" link Credits}.

  The USAELOT is the keymap that prints out the normal Latin characters you are
  used to. The ELOT928 keymap, when active, prints out Greek characters. @{"Here" link Keys}
  is the correspondance of the Latin and Greek characters on the keyboard.

  But these keymaps have something special. You can print Greek when the USAELOT
  keymap is active if you press ALT+letter, and correspondingly you can print
  Latin when the ELOT928 keymap is active, if you press ALT+letter. This is to
  provide a quick way of entering characters from the alternate set, without
  having to change the active keymap. Also if you press ALT+number you can find
  some rarely used characters that you sometimes might need (like ˋ or Ý).
@endnode

@node Keys "EPA Greek Workbench - The keymap layouts"

      @{b}Latin     Greek@{ub}

        a       alpha
        b       beta
        c       psee
        d       delta
        e       epsilon
        f       fee
        g       gamma
        h       eeta
        i       yiota
        j       ksee
        k       kappa
        l       lamda
        m       mee
        n       nee
        o       omicron
        p       pee
        q       ;
        r       ro
        s       seegma
        t       taf
        u       theta
        v       omega
        w       final seegma
        x       hee
        y       eepseelon
        z       zeta

  To add a tone to the Greek vowels press `;' (usually to the right of the `l'
  key) and then the desired vowel. This holds for capital vowels also.
@endnode

@node Fonts "EPA Greek Workbench - The supplied Latin-Greek fonts"

  There are five fonts supplied with "EPA Greek Workbench". They all come from
  the original ones in the Fonts Disk. They were changed and extended to contain
  the Greek characters, by @{"me" link Contact}, using @{"Typeface" link Credits}.
  The font helveticagr_SH.font came from the helveticagr.font using the program
  @{"SHADOWMAKER Version 1.5" link Credits}.

    @{b}topazgr.font@{ub}
      The famous topaz.font with Greek characters too. The @{"ReplaceTopaz" link ReplaceTopaz}
      program patches the ROM topaz.font with it.
    @{b}couriergr.font@{ub}
      The courier font extended with Greek characters. It is a bitmap font, and
      I use it (size 13) as system font, so it is the font in my shells.
    @{b}helveticagr.font@{ub}
      The helvetica outline font but with Greek characters too. I use it (size
      11) as screen font.
    @{b}helveticagr_SH.font@{ub}
      This is an outline multicolor font, designed specially to be used as icon
      font. The letters are white with a black shadow, so that the icon names
      are visible under any circumstances, any background light or dark. It
      comes in one size only, the one @{"I" link Contact} use ;-)
    @{b}greek-prop.font@{ub}
      Just another font that used to be Latin only (p0t-prop was the name I
      think) and I extended it by designing Greek characters too. Note that it
      is a bitmap font, not a proportional one as the name may suggest.

  You can look in Aminet for more Greek fonts. For example a nice set of
  proportional fonts that you can use as defaults for your web browser, is
  MPFonts_intell.lha which can be found on the text/ifont directory of Aminet.
@endnode

@node ToggleKeymap "EPA Greek Workbench - The ToggleKeymap program"

  @{b}ToggleKeymap is Copyright 1996-97 Elias Papanikolaou (EPA)@{ub}

  The ToggleKeymap program, when run, toggles the active keymap between @{"USAELOT" link keymaps}
  and @{"ELOT928" link keymaps}. These keymaps must exist in the drawer pointed to by the assign
  KEYMAPS: (if you followed the @{"installation" link Installation} instructions, they will be there...)

  If everything is ok, the active keymap of the system is changed, just as if
  you had run the `Input' preferences program, selected the keymap, and clicked
  Use or Save.

  But there is a @{"problem" link Problems}.
@endnode

@node ReplaceTopaz "EPA Greek Workbench - The ReplaceTopaz program"

  @{b}ReplaceTopaz is Copyright 1996-97 Elias Papanikolaou (EPA)@{ub}

  The ReplaceTopaz program, when executed, patches the topaz.font that is in
  ROM and extensively used by the system, with the supplied @{"topazgr.font" link fonts}.
  The topazgr.font has to be there, in the FONTS: drawer (it will be there if
  you followed the @{"installation" link Installation} instructions).

  You don't need to run it, just execute it once. It performs the patch and
  exits. You can execute it at any time, meaning it could be the last thing in
  your s:User-Startup sequence. The installer will ask you to add a line like
  this in your s:User-Startup:

    C:ReplaceTopaz

  If it has not done it (maybe because you refused) you can do it yourself.
  Edit the s:User-Startup with your favourite editor and add the above line
  anywhere.
@endnode

@node KeymapChange "EPA Greek Workbench - Automating the keymap change"

  To automate the keymap change, assign a hot key to execute the @{"ToggleKeymap" link ToggleKeymap}
  program, so that everytime you press that hotkey, the keymap is changed.

  In order to do that, you can use the FKey preferences program, or, if you are
  already using something like MCP (that's the one I use, I recommend it), MCX,
  or a similar multi purpose commodity, you can use that instead of FKey.

  The best choice, in my opinion, is to @{i}use the program that you already use@{ui}
  for hotkeys. If you don't use any, use FKey.

  Example 1 (FKey, these actions can also be performed by the installation
             script):

        Drag the `FKey' program out of the drawer `SYS:Tools/Commodities' and
        into the `SYS:WBStartup' drawer (if it is not already there). Double
        click on it to run it. Click on `New Key'. Enter something like
        `ALT RETURN' on the gadget above, then goto to the cycle gadget under
        `Command' and click until you see `Run Program'. Under the
        `Command Parameters' enter `C:ToggleKeymap'. Finally, from the Project
        menu choose `Save Defined Keys'.
        Now whenever you press ALT and RETURN simultaniously, the keymap should
        change.

  Example 2 (MCP, @{"my" link Contact} setting):

        In MCPPrefs, I have activated Hotkeys in the main page, and in the
        hotkeys page, in the `Execute Command' option I have defined one hotkey
        (ALT RETURN) to execute "SYS:Bin/ToggleKeymap". So when I press the
        keys ALT and RETURN simultaniously, the keymap is toggled. If it was
        Latin it becomes Greek, and vice versa.
@endnode

@node PatchTopaz "EPA Greek Workbench - Patching the ROM Topaz 8 font"

  The situation in a nutshell:

  The fonts used for "EPA Greek Workbench" conform to the ELOT 928 standard (the
  most dominand for Greek ASCII character positions). According to this standard
  the Greek characters in a font can be found in the higher ASCII positions (128
  and up).
  Now, the topaz.font has no Greek characters in that positions. And regretfully
  there are programs that only use topaz.font. Even more regretfully, this bad
  example is set by the standard system preferences programs (those that are
  found in the SYS:Prefs drawer) and requesters (like the `execute command' or
  the `rename' requester).
  So for programs like that, the only solution to make them use a different font
  (a Greek one) is a patch.

  What you have to do:

  Use the supplied @{"ReplaceTopaz" link ReplaceTopaz} program, or @{i}if you are already@{ui} using a multi
  function commodity like MCP or MCX, do the same thing by turning on an
  analogous patch (it it called NoTopaz in MCP) and supplying the @{"topazgr.font" link fonts}
  as the substitute for the topaz.font.
@endnode

@node Problems "EPA Greek Workbench - Problems, suggestions, etc."

1. When using `ToggleKeymap' the keymap of the already opened shells is not
   changed. This is because each console uses a private keymap (and not the
   global one) that it copies from the global when it is first started. So
   each shell keeps the keymap that was active when it was first opened. If you
   have a program that can change the keymap of all opened shells too, feel
   free to use it. I will try to improve my ToggleKeymap program in the next
   release. On the other hand, if you just want to type a few characters of
   the alternate set on a shell, you can use ALT+letter (see @{"keymaps" link Keymaps}).

   If you have

         problems installing or other,
         suggestions for alternate translations of some words,
         other suggestions,

   find spelling/syntactic/grammatic or other errors,

   please @{b}do@{ub} contact @{"me" link Contact}.
@endnode

@node "History" "EPA Greek Workbench - History"
@{b}Version 1.0@{ub} - November 1996

- First public release

@{b}Version 1.1@{ub} - January 1997

- Fixed and greatly enhanced the installer script that did nothing if the user
  was Novice or Intermediate. This script has taken me more time than anything
  else. Try it!
- Supplied the program `ReplaceTopaz' and the font topazgr to help patch the
  ROM Topaz 8 font that is used in the standard system preferences and
  requesters.
- Changed the program `SetKeymap' to `ToggleKeymap' so that now you don't have
  to use 2 hotkeys to change between keymaps. Just 1 that toggles ;-)
- Minor modifications to the Greek translations of some words.

@{b}Version 1.3@{ub} - June 1997

- Certain message numbers of the utilities.catalog changed(!) from OS3.0 to
  OS3.1. The affected part was the menu of `Multiview'. As a result some menu
  components were in English under OS3.1. Fixed.
- Minor addition in prefs.catalog.
- Minor change in workbench.catalog.
- Added the greek-prop font, and a backdrop pattern in the distribution.
- Added an icon for the EPAGrWb drawer (both normal and newicon)
@endnode

@node "Future" "EPA Greek Workbench - Future"

  The future of "EPA Greek Workbench" may include:

  ñ improvement of the translations (with @{i}your@{ui} help)
  ñ improvement of the ToggleKeymap program so that it changes the keymap
    on open shells too
  ñ anything you ask for
@endnode

